==English==
===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /kɑ:/

===Etymology 1===
Egyptian ''k3''.

====Noun====
'''ka'''
# a spiritual part of the [[soul]] in Egyptian mythology, which survived after death
#:*'''1983''': Then, I wondered how long I must wait before seeing my Double, but if I recalled, the '''Ka''' was not supposed to appear before the seventy days of embalming were done. — Norman Mailer, ''Ancient Evenings''

=== Etymology 2===
From the Latin phrase ''[[fricantem]] [[frica]]'' <!-- ''[[Muli]] [[mutuo]] [[scabunt]]'' -->
====Transitive verb====
'''ka''' (''inflections not attested'')
# To serve, in the phrase ''"Ka me, ka thee"''.
#:'''quotations''':
#:*"'''Ka''' me, '''ka''' thee, is a proverb all over the world." &mdash; Sir [[w:Walter Scott|Walter Scott]], ''[[w:Kenilworth (novel)|Kenilworth]]''
==== References ====
* [http://bootlegbooks.com/Reference/PhraseAndFable/data/693.html Brewer's Dictionary of Phrase and Fable]

